'''Yanko Ivanov Sakazov''' ({{lang-bg|<U+042F><U+043D><U+043A><U+043E> <U+0418><U+0432><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432> <U+0421><U+0430><U+043A><U+044A><U+0437><U+043E><U+0432>}}, 24 September 1860<U+2013>2 February 1941<ref name="histenc">{{cite book |title=<U+0415><U+043B><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442><U+0440><U+043E><U+043D><U+043D><U+043E> <U+0438><U+0437><U+0434><U+0430><U+043D><U+0438><U+0435> "<U+0418><U+0441><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F>" |language=Bulgarian |last=<U+0411><U+0430><U+043A><U+0430><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432> |first=<U+0413><U+0435><U+043E><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438> |coauthors=<U+041C><U+0438><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D> <U+041A><U+0443><U+043C><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432> |publisher=<U+0422><U+0440><U+0443><U+0434>, <U+0421><U+0438><U+0440><U+043C><U+0430> |location=<U+0421><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+044F> |year=2003 |isbn=9844830679 |chapter=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430><U+043D><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438>, <U+0413><U+0435><U+043E><U+0440><U+0433><U+0438> <U+0418><U+0432><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432> (1847<U+2013>4.I.1904) }}</ref><ref name="bio">Heumos, Peter. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=VD-uiXwY7PIC Europ<U+00E4>ischer Sozialismus im Kalten Krieg: Briefe und Berichte 1944 - 1948]''. Frankfurt/Main [u.a.]: Campus-Verl, 2004. p. 55</ref>) was a [[Bulgaria]]n [[socialist]] politician.

A native of the northeastern city of [[Shumen]], Sakazov went abroad for studies during his youth, studying in [[Western Europe]] and [[Russia]]. He was a student of natural sciences, philosophy and history in [[Germany]], biology in [[England]] and literature and art criticism in [[France]].<ref name="histenc"/> After his return to Bulgaria, he was one of the founders of the Social Democratic Union in Bulgaria in 1892.<ref name="bio"/>

Sakazov edited the Shumen-based publication ''Den'' ('Day') between 1891 and 1896.<ref>Linden, Marcel van der, and J<U+00FC>rgen Rojahn. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=wMkUAAAAIAAJ The Formation of Labour Movements, 1870-1914: An International Perspective. Contributions to the history of labour and society, v. 2]''. [[Leiden]]: E.J. Brill, 1990. p. 418</ref>

Sakazov was one of two candidates of the [[Bulgarian Social Democratic Workers Party]] elected to the [[National Assembly of Bulgaria|National Assembly]] in the [[Bulgarian parliamentary election, 1894|1894 election]] (the other being Gabrovski).<ref name="form2"/> Sakazov represented the rural constituency Novi Pazar. Sakazov and Gabrovski were the two first socialist parliamentarians in the history of Bulgaria.<ref name="form2">Linden, Marcel van der, and J<U+00FC>rgen Rojahn. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=wMkUAAAAIAAJ The Formation of Labour Movements, 1870-1914: An International Perspective. Contributions to the history of labour and society, v. 2]''. [[Leiden]]: E.J. Brill, 1990. p. 414</ref> Sakazov became a parliamentarian again in 1911, and as the sole socialist deputy in the National Assembly he voted against increased military spending in 1912.<ref>Linden, Marcel van der, and J<U+00FC>rgen Rojahn. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=wMkUAAAAIAAJ The Formation of Labour Movements, 1870-1914: An International Perspective. Contributions to the history of labour and society, v. 2]''. [[Leiden]]: E.J. Brill, 1990. p. 416</ref>

In 1900 Sakazov founded the publication ''Obshto delo'' ('Common Action'), around which the moderate faction of the party rallied. Sakazov's followers became known as 'Broad Socialists'. In 1903 the party was divided into two, with Sakazov's faction forming the [[Bulgarian Social Democratic Workers Party (Broad Socialists)]].<ref name="form">Linden, Marcel van der, and J<U+00FC>rgen Rojahn. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=wMkUAAAAIAAJ The Formation of Labour Movements, 1870-1914: An International Perspective. Contributions to the history of labour and society, v. 2]''. [[Leiden]]: E.J. Brill, 1990. p. 406</ref><ref>Nation, R. C. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=nU8jMfkZ-OsC War on war: Lenin, the Zimmerwald Left, and the origins of communist internationalism]''. Durham [u.a.]: Duke Univ. Pr, 1989. p. 12</ref>

Sakazov served as Minister for Trade, Industry and Labour between 1918 and 1919.<ref name="bio"/>

Sakazov was the representative of the Bulgarian Broad Socialists in the Executive of the [[Labour and Socialist International]] from 1923 to 1940 (the entire period of existence of the international). Until August 1925 Sakazov's seat was shared with the [[Yugoslav]] socialist leader [[<U+200E><U+017D>ivko Topalovi<U+0107>]].<ref>Kowalski, Werner. ''[http://books.google.com/books?id=83QdPwAACAAJ Geschichte der sozialistischen arbeiter-internationale: 1923 - 19]''. Berlin: Dt. Verl. d. Wissenschaften, 1985. p. 283</ref>

